  "citations": [
    "Gruber, J., & Saez, E. (2002). The elasticity of taxable income: evidence and implications. Journal of Public Economics.",
    "Saez, E., Slemrod, J., & Giertz, S. H. (2012). The elasticity of taxable income with respect to marginal tax rates: A critical review. Journal of Economic Literature."
  ],
  "reasoning_summary": "The literature on the elasticity of taxable income (ETI) generally finds higher elasticities for high-income earners due to greater opportunities for tax avoidance and shifting. Early estimates (e.g., Feldstein 1995) were very high (>1), but subsequent work controlling for mean reversion and using broader panels (like Gruber and Saez 2002) found a central estimate around 0.4 for high earners. The Saez, Slemrod, and Giertz (2012) review suggests a consensus ETI of around 0.12 to 0.4 overall, with higher estimates at the top of the distribution."
}

